Dear David,

A PMA company must have a minimum investment plan of IDR 10 billion 
(excluding land and buildings). However, this does not mean that the 
company must physically inject this amount into Indonesia. 
Alternatively, shareholders can sign a capital declaration, stating that 
their liability is limited to the nominal paid-up capital recorded in 
the company’s documents. If the paid-up capital has not been fully 
settled, it will be recorded as shareholders' receivables in the 
financial statements.

The conversion to a PMA company will not directly affect the company’s 
existing bank accounts. However, some banks may require updates to 
company records, including changes to the Articles of Association and 
business license status.

A PMA company can hire both local and foreign employees. However, hiring 
foreign employees requires obtaining:

  * RPTKA (Foreign Worker Utilization Plan)
  * Work permit (IMTA/Notifikasi)

Certain positions, particularly in HR, legal, and some administrative 
roles, may be restricted to Indonesian nationals under labor 
regulations. While there are no major operational restrictions for 
distribution/trading activities under a PMA structure, compliance with 
tax regulations and the Investment Activity Report (LKPM) is required.

Please let me know if you need further clarification or if you’d like to 
schedule a discussion to go over these points in more detail.

Thank you.


Best regards,

